ent, England":"Woodchurch, Kent, England"},"en":{"1180–1272":"1180–1272","1180–1219":"1180–1219","1219–1267":"1219–1267","1160–1200":"1160–1200","1162–Female":"1162–Deceased","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1267":"1267","about 1180":"about 1180","1200":"1200","1272":"1272","1162":"1162","before 1219":"before 1219","1160":"1160","1219":"1219","1180":"1180","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","London, London, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Woodchurch, Kent, England":"Woodchurch, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Harvey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Hervei</i>, also found as <i>Herveu</i>, <i>Hervé</i>, and <i>Hervi</i>. The name <i>Herveu</i> or <i>Herv(e)i</i> was borne by a number of Bretons at the Norman Conquest and, as such, represents a French form of the Old Breton name <i>Hoiearnviu</i> or <i>Hærviu</i> (see   Herve  ). Among Normans <i>Herve(i)</i> or <i>Herv(e)i</i> was also a French form of ancient Germanic <i>Hariwic</i>, <i>Herewic</i> (from <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>wīg</i> ‘war’), with intervocalic /w/ becoming /v/ in Old French. The Breton and ancient Germanic names were commonly Latinized as <i>Herve(i)us</i> and <i>Hervic(i)us</i> respectively but, since their most common vernacular forms in Old French were indistinguishable, the Latin forms were also sometimes interchangeable, especially <i>Herveus</i>.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hAirmheadhaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Airmheadhach</i>’, a personal name probably meaning ‘esteemed’. It seems to be a derivative of <i>Airmheadh</i>, the name borne by a mythological physician.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEarchaidh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Earchadh</i>’, a personal name of uncertain origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Arvey","meanings":["English: variant of   Harvey  ."]},{"name":"Harvie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Harvey  ."]},{"name":"Herve","meanings":["Breton (<b>Hervé</b>): from the Old Breton personal name <i>Hoiearnviu</i>, composed of the elements <i>hoiarn</i> ‘iron’ and <i>viu</i> ‘blazing’, or <i>Hærviu</i>, with the first element meaning ‘battle’ or ‘fort’.","French (<b>Hervé</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Hariwig</i>, composed of the elements <i>hari</i> ‘army’ and <i>wig</i> ‘battle’. Compare   Harvey  ."]},{"name":"Hervey","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Harvey  ."]},{"name":"Havey","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Harvey  , although some instances in the historical records may be spelling errors."]},{"name":"Harvison","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): patronymic from the personal name   Harvey   + ‘son’."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":44,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":79,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Walter Harvey was born in 1180, in London, Middlesex, England, his father, Walter Harvey I, was 20 and his mother, Elizabeth Chapman, was 18. He married Lady Mary Dering before 1219, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1272, in his hometown, at the age of 92, and was buried in England."},"et":{"1180–1272":"1180–1272","1180–1219":"1180–1219","1219–1267":"1219–1267","1160–1200":"1160–1200","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1267":"1267","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1200":"1200","1272":"1272","1162":"1162","before 1219":"enne 1219","1160":"1160","1219":"1219","1180":"1180","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","London, London, England":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Woodchurch, Kent, England":"Woodchurch, Kent, England"},"fi":{"1180–1272":"1180–1272","1180–1219":"1180–1219","1219–1267":"1219–1267","1160–1200":"1160–1200","1162–Female":"1162–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1267":"1267","about 1180":"noin 1180","1200":"1200","1272":"1272","1162":"1162","before 1219":"ennen vuotta 1219","1160":"1160","1219":"1219","1180":"1180","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","London, London, 